{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06bb0d8d-6c9c-4595-9bbc-c32e16bc6715","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect a trace:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                        # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** — open in Visual Studio, VS Code (with the .NET profiler extension), or PerfView on Windows. To convert for **Speedscope** (browser-based):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use **`dotnet-trace`** from a [sidecar or ephemeral container](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/pods/ephemeral-containers/).\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over interactive stop to avoid forgetting a running trace.\n- If you need OS-level context (native frames, kernel), use **`dotnet-counters`** first to confirm managed CPU, then escalate to `perf` + `PerfCollect` if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e02bdebc-8cd8-4f72-ac26-e62d7c61f3ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"7651:2FE433:D5A5AA:FA4F02:69FE8D8B"},"id":"66a0e915-4a3d-4909-95d3-b32abe5e6d1e","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:27:50.661Z","parentId":"795af35b-8ced-49bb-9b25-7668fe182f83"}
